<html><HEAD>
Daily Press Revue 95 1996-04-26
</title>
<HR SIZE=3><CENTER>
<H1>Daily Press Review</H1>
<P><B>Date 1996-04-26
<P> Number 95</B>
</center>
<HR SIZE=3> 
</head><P></BODY>
<OL>
<B><LI>Chernobyl</B><P>     On 26/4/86, Chernobyl-4 exploded releasing 200 times as much radiation as Hiroshima
and Nagasaki combined. The accident played a substantial role in collapse of Soviet
Union; environmental and economic costs can not yet be estimated. First reaction of
officials was cover-up; locals were told it was just a fire and there was no danger
so people suffered unnecessary radiation before evacuation of first 100 000. Maps
showing extent of radiation were released in 1989 and more people were evacuated.
As facts were known, Ukraine and Belarus were outraged; reaction mobilized national
movements which changed Soviet politics. Chernobyl accident reportedly destroyed
Soviet Defence Minister's belief that a nuclear war could be fought and won. Partly
because of cover up and partly because of prior poor health data, full health
effects unlikely ever to be known; Russia uses official figure of 31 deaths,
Ukrainian Government estimates 8000 and Ukrainian Greens, 32 000. Ukrainian
official figures report 4229 deaths since 1986 as result of accident which include
2929 'liquidators'. 800 000 heavily exposed 'liquidators' are scattered around CIS.
Clear evidence of wave of childhood thyroid cancer; too soon to know effects on
adults. Other illnesses also being tracked. US expert says post-Chernobyl thryroid
cancer cases 'could have been prevented' if authorities had provided foods such as
uncontaminated powdered milk. Families living in contaminated areas have twice as
many genetic mutations as expected and they will be passed to future generations.
Exposures continue; 400 000 people have now been evacuated and at least 300 000
more live on dangerously contaminated land. 30-million drink contaminated water.
Belarus estimates it spends 15% of GDP on Chernobyl; Ukraine 5% of budget. Poverty
said to scare Ukrainians more than Chernobyl aftermath. A few hours before
Chernobyl anniversary, minor release of radiation when filter was changed at
Chernobyl-3 detracted from commemorations; radiation was cleaned up overnight and
no threat to environment; incident was said to be because of careless work. Fires
around Chernobyl earlier in week hurt no one and there was only minor rise in
radiation. Details of 11/95 incident which was reclassed at INES level '3'. Swiss
energy politics after 1986 accident reported. Germany closed eastern European NPPs
following accident and future of nuclear power there influenced by it. Immediately
after accident, in Munich radiation rose for a short time to ten times normal level
and plants and wild animals are still affected by caesium. Western help for
Chernobyl said to be 'out of control'. Austria commemorates Chernobyl. Following
Chernobyl, Austria has campaigned for closure of NPPs in neighbouring lands. Visit
to 'sarcophagus' and tour of site reported. US medicines flown to Chernobyl
victims. President Yeltsin thanks those who fought the fire 10 years ago. Police
confronted protestors near Chernobyl as thousands of mourners gathered round a
monument to dead in Slavutych, a new town built to rehouse staff after explosion.
Belarus President says authorities have no moral right to prevent people returning
to Chernobyl region. Chernobyl symbolizes 'everything wrong with Ukraine's energy
sector'.
<P>(IHT, T, FT, S, WSJ, I, SN, NZZ, SDZ, DP, FAZ, EP, REUTER, ENS, ENER, 25,26/4, NN,
4/96)<P>- Ukraine, Belarus, Russia, CIS, Eastern Europe, Germany, Austria, IAEA-INES,
US, Switzerland, UK, IAEA, WHO -       
 <P></OL><HR></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
