<html><HEAD>
Daily Press Revue 94 1996-04-26
</title>
<HR SIZE=3><CENTER>
<H1>Daily Press Review</H1>
<P><B>Date 1996-04-26
<P> Number 94</B>
</center>
<HR SIZE=3> 
</head><P></BODY>
<OL><B><LI>Chernobyl</B><P>   Chernobyl burden on Ukraine's collapsed health system.
<P>(REUTER, 25/4)  <P> - Ukraine -
<P><B><LI>Nuclear safety</B><P>   Bulgarian and Romanian nuclear experts meet. Fuel transport accord expected.
<P>(BBC MONITORING SERVICE, 25/4)  <P>        - Bulgaria, Romania -
<P><B><LI>Radwaste, fuel</B><P>   Clinton administration threatens veto of radwaste policy act. NRC OK's Trojan
decommissioning plan. NRC questions TVA's decommissioning ability. INEL fined
for 61 violations of hazardous waste laws. Report concludes Ward Valley site
will not leak. Two unexpected hitches delay start up of new vitrification
plant at Savannah River. Duke Power Co awards waste processing contract.
Irish campaign against alleged dumping of Sellafield radwaste in Irish Sea.
Ukraine discusses programme for treating radwaste. Train carrying radioactive
iron waste travels from Czech Republic through Austria to Italy. EdF at 50
faces deregulation and decommissioning fund segregation. 
<P>(NEI INFO, NYT, ED, NW, BBC MON SERV, K, 8, 12, 15, 16, 18, 19, 24, 25/4)<P>- US, Ireland,
UK, Ukraine, Austria, Czech Rep, Italy, France, EU -
<P><B><LI>Radiation, health</B><P> NRC disagreement on whether to take first two hours after an accident or 
'worst' two hours for calculating dose limits from postulated accidents for
future reactor designs.
<P>(NW, 18/4)<P> - US -
<P><B><LI>Incidents</B><P>   Japanese NPP at Onagawa temporarily shut down on 24/4 after pressure rise.
Contaminated water spillage during overhaul of Slovak Bohunice NPP on 15/4.
<P>(BBC MONITORING SERVICE, 25/4)   <P>  - Japan, Slovak Republic -
<P><B><LI>Nuclear energy</B><P>   Federal Rep of Yugoslavia sets up commission for nuclear energy. Completion
of Mochovce NPP seen by Slovakia as 'litmus test' of East-West co-operation;
revamped visitor centre opens. Public opinion of nuclear energy in France and
Germany. Ukraine to restructure nuclear industry. Nuclear power status, 1995.
Robert Donovan, President and CEO of ABB Inc.died in crash which killed US
Secretary of Commerce, Ron Brown. China-Russia nuclear energy trade deals.
Inauguration of Romania's Cernavoda NPP. Norway buys into Swedish nuclear
operations. Scottish Nuclear achieves record output for two AGRs. Florida
utility lays off workers to cut costs. Hatch-1 uprate following Hatch-2's. 
<P>(BBC MON SERV, ENER, ENS, REUTER, NW, 18, 23-25/4)<P>-Former-Yugoslavia, Slovak Rep, 
France, Germany, UK, US, Ukraine, world, IAEA, Romania, China, Russia, Norway, Sweden -
<P><B><LI>UN</B><P> More on UN financial crisis.
<P>(TG, 17,18/4)<P> - UN -
<P><B><LI>Energy, environment</B><P> Challenge of electricity for all. How market forces affect least-cost 
plans of power utilities. International power connections. Power sector
regulation. Plan to join Arab electricity grid to Europe's. Production of
electricity and heat in one power plant in France. EU energy policy; EU CO2
emissions could increase 5% above 1990 levels by 2000. New study challenges
climate models; European Science and Environment Forum publication: 'The
Global Warming Debate'. 'Is global warming climate change?' World Energy
Council says forthcoming report on global warming with recommendations for
policy makers by International Panel on Climate Change is deficient and of
little value. Call for global monitoring of environment. Water resource
management. Green economy and eco taxes. Interview with James Lovelock, known
for Gaia Theory. Sustainability. Pollution at North Pole. US puts environment
at top of agenda. UK study links ozone and asthma attacks. Austria has motto:
'From Rio to Austria' for World Environment Day, 5/6. CO2 emissions rise in
Austria; Vienna will not meet ozone target. EU environment information system
to be developed at Seibersdorf with Germany and France. Windpower in Austria
and EU. Court stops construction of Austrian hydro plant. Solar energy in
Austria. Mexico needs more structured approach to overcome pollution; private
investment in power plants. Oil prices 'unlikely to rise much' before 2000.
Shell accused of pollution in Turkey. Vietnam warns China over oil in South
China Sea. Final productive phase in North Sea oil fields. Qatar contract for
huge gas project. Landfill gas power potential. Restructuring of deregulated
Nordic electricity market. Russia-China natural gas deal. Pakistan energy.
Foreign investment in CIS and Eastern European energy projects.
Liberalization of Poland's energy market. Hungarian utilities sale. Bid to
turn slaughtered cattle into electricity. Oil in Asia Pacific.    
<P>(UI NB, 16/96, INDIAN JP&RVD, 12/95, FT, NS, SDZ, LM, WP, CSM, MEED, NAT, NWK, IHT, K, DP, 
NZZ, DTEL, T, SN, S, 27, 29/3, 5, 6, 9-13, 15, 16, 19, 23, 25/4, ENERGY IN EURO, OPEC BULL, 
NEW INTL, 1, 3, 4/95)<P>-worldwide, India, Arab League, Europe, France, China, Russia, UK, 
US, North Pole, Austria, Germany, Mexico, CIS, E, Europe, Qatar, Scandinavia, WEC, IPCC,
 Turkey, Vietnam, Poland, Hungary, UN - 
<P><P></OL><HR></BODY></HTML>
