<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Concluding Press Conference
International Forum on the Safety of RBMK Reactors</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><HR><P>
<CENTER>
<H2>Concluding Press Conference<BR>
International Forum on the Safety of RBMK Reactors</H2>
<P>
<I>(Editor's Note:  This is an unofficial summary of the press briefing and not an official record.)</CENTER></I>
<P><HR><P>
Further improvements -- and the financial assistance to make them -- are needed to upgrade the safety of RBMK reactors,  fifteen of which are operating in three 
countries -- Lithuania, Russia, and Ukraine -- and to reinforce the structure known as the sarcophagus built around the Chernobyl reactor destroyed in the 1986 
accident, in the view of international nuclear safety experts.
<P>
At a press conference 3 April 1996 at IAEA headquarters in Vienna, Prof. Adolf Birkhofer of Germany, Academician V.A. Sidorenko of Russia, and Mr. A.E. Smyshlyaev 
of Ukraine responded to questions about safety issues discussed by experts attending the International Forum:  One Decade After Chernobyl -- Nuclear Safety 
Aspects,  held 1-3 April and jointly organized by the IAEA and UN Department of Humanitarian Affairs.  Conclusions of the Forum -- which Prof. Birkhofer served 
as Chairman --  are being reported to the International Conference on Chernobyl being convened in Vienna  8-12 April by the IAEA, European Commission, and World 
Health Organization.
<P>
Major points made at the press conference:
<UL>
<LI>Prof. Birkhofer said he now had a better understanding of the complicated RBMK reactors and of the remedial measures and safety improvements that had been -- 
and were still being -- made.  Pressed to say whether he would want to see any reactors withdrawn from service, he said he personally would favour that action 
in some cases.  However, he said this was a matter for the national regulatory/licensing authorities in the countries concerned, not for Western nuclear 
engineers who could only assist, co-operate and give their opinions and advice to the affected States and their own authorities.  He stressed that, irrespective 
of whether a unit was slated to be phased out or not, safety improvements -- with Western financial support -- had to be made.
<P>
<LI>Regarding the possibility of a serious accident, Prof. Birkhofer said an explosion like the one which destroyed Chernobyl Unit 4, an RBMK reactor, should no 
longer be possible at RBMKs given the safety improvements that have been made.  However, he said he could not state categorically that an explosion could not 
happen.  Whereas the same combination of circumstances that led to the Chernobyl accident in 1986 could virtually be ruled out (given the technical changes that 
had been made to RBMKs), there was a residual risk of multiple fuel channel failure that could trigger a large release, given the lack of a containment structure
like the ones surrounding Western-type reactors.  But an explosion triggered by a reactor excursion, compounded as it was in 1986 by operating and regulatory 
violations, was very unlikely to recur today. 
<P>
<LI>Academician Sidorenko said he regretted that to date Western financial and hardware assistance had been relatively insignificant.  The biggest sum was US $30 
million promised by the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development (EBRD), but this was still in the pipeline.  Only in the last two years had the 
emphasis shifted to technical assistance, which he welcomed.  However, he believed about US $130 milllion per unit was the scale of assistance required to 
improve safety levels adequately.  He added that the oldest Russian RBMK units were having their operating permits extended only one year at a time, permitting 
review of their performance, the improvements that had been made, and decisions about further required improvements.
<P>
<LI>Concerning the Chernobyl sarcophagus, Prof. Birkhofer said there were two risks that had been discussed at the Forum:  the possible collapse of the roof and 
the possible recriticality of a small amount of undamaged fuel if it came into contact with water.  On the first of these possibilities, he said the existing 
sarcophagus by necessity had been built in extremely arduous conditions, without some of the normal construction features that would ensure structural integrity 
and resistance to extreme outside pressures.  In such a case, radioactive dust could be resuspended and escape, affecting the site and the 30 kilometer exclusion
zone.  This being so, there is a need to take short-term measures to buttress the structure, pending decision on and implementation of a second sarcophagus 
structure.  On the second issue, recriticality, Prof. Birkhofer said this was a remote risk but something that could not be dismissed, based on theoretical 
studies conducted in Russia and Ukraine.  If such an event occurred, with water leaking into the sarcophagus and coming in contact with the fuel, then this 
could result in a radioactive release both inside and outside the structure, but probably not producing sufficient energy to provoke an explosion.  There was a 
need to help Ukraine finance further studies and analysis in this area to obtain a better idea of the current status and improvements that are needed, taking 
account of Russian and Ukrainian expertise.
</UL>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
</BODY>
</HTML>


