<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> PR 96/5 - 21 March 1996 - International IAEA Forum on the Safety of RBMK Reactors</TITLE>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<B>21 March 1996
<BR>
PR 96/5</B>
<P>
<CENTER>
<H2>INTERNATIONAL IAEA FORUM ON THE SAFETY OF RBMK REACTORS </H2>
</CENTER>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<P>
The nuclear reactor at Chernobyl, Ukraine, which was destroyed in the accident ten years ago was a Soviet-designed nuclear power plant known by the Russian acronym RBMK. Today 15 RBMK power reactors are producing electricity in three States: 11 units in Russia, 2 in Ukraine and 2 in Lithuania. To review remedial measures and actions taken since the Chernobyl accident the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and the Department for Humanitarian Affairs of the United Nations will organize in Vienna from 1 to 3 April 1996 an International Forum on Nuclear Safety Aspects of RBMK Reactors. In addition the Forum will discuss questions of the containment structure of the protective building built around the accident reactor at Chernobyl - the so called sarcophagus.
<P>
Over the past decade, a considerable amount of work has been carried out by Russian designers and operators to improve the safety of RBMK reactors and to eliminate the causes that led to the Chernobyl accident. As a result, major design and operational modifications have been implemented. However, safety concerns remain, particularly regarding the first-generation units.
<P>
In addition to these actions taken by the Russian designers and operators, the IAEA has  initiated in 1992 the RBMK safety programme with the aim to consolidate results of various national, bilateral and multilateral activities and to establish international consensus on required safety improvements and related priorities. Through this programme international assistance is provided to both regulatory and operating organizations with a basis for technical and financial decisions. Activities of the IAEA's RBMK safety programme are co-ordinated with those of an international consortium on the "Safety of Design Solutions and Operation of Nuclear Power Plants with RBMK Reactors" established under auspices of the European Commission.
<P>
The IAEA has now prepared a consolidated list of design and operational safety issues for RBMK reactors. It suggests safety upgradings in the following fields: Core Design and Core Monitoring, Instrumentation and Control, Pressure Boundary Integrity, Incident and Accident Analysis, Safety and Support Systems, Fire Protection and Operational Safety.
<P>
Discussions at the International Forum will concentrate on the Causes of the Chernobyl Accident; Remedial Actions; National, Bilateral and International Safety Improvement Programmes; and Chernobyl Sarcophagus. There will be reports on the current status and safety improvements of the RBMK reactors at Chernobyl, Ignalina, Kursk, Leningrad and Smolensk.
<P>
The papers presented will be available and there will be a press briefing on Wednesday, 3 April 1996, at 16.00 p.m. in the IAEA Meeting Room C07 V at the Vienna International Centre .  
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE="1">
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG BORDER="0" SRC="/worldatom/images/backtomain.jpg" ALT="Back to listing of Press Releases"></A>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE="1">
<P>
</BODY>
