<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Summary of Sessions
</TITLE>
<META name="author" content="quevenco@adpo1.iaea.or.at">
<META name="expires" content="31 October 1995">
<META name="url" content="http://www.iaea.or.at/worldatom/thisweek/preview/summary1.html">
<META name="type" content="edited">
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER>
<H2>International Symposium on Electricity, Health and the 
Environment</H2>
<H3>Summary of Sessions</H3>
<HR>
<P>
<B>| <A HREF="#sum1">17 October</A> | <A HREF="#sum2">18 October</A> | 19 October |</B>
</CENTER>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="sum1">
<B>Tuesday, 17 October</B></A>
<P>
The first technical session of the Symposium, chaired by the Director 
of Tata Energy Research Institute (India), Dr. Rajendra Pachauri, set 
the stage by highlighting the key issues to be addressed for 
implementing sustainable electricity policies in developing countries, 
countries in transition and industrialised countries.  The different 
view points that were presented illustrated that there is a wide range 
of issues of concern to decision makers in various regions and that 
there may be greatly different priorities according to the level of 
social, economic and industrial development in a given country.  As 
already pointed out by Dr. Blix in his opening statement on the first 
day of the Symposium, developing countries starving for energy are 
placing emphasis in the first place on adequate electricity supply and 
on mitigating local environmental impacts.  Countries in transition 
are faced with financing difficulties and adaptation of industrial 
structures to market economy.  Industrialised countries that are 
implementing a number of technical options and policy measures for 
alleviating health and environmental impacts of electricity systems, 
need further experience to assess the effectiveness of alternative 
strategies.  Dr. Pachauri highlighted in his concluding remarks the 
need for international co-operation in order to enhance exchange of 
experience and technology transfer, and facilitate the implementation 
of measures that benefit to several countries and address a range of 
local, transboundary and global issues. Dr. Pachauri stressed also 
that the sustainability goals require to keep  open all technological 
options, including nuclear power, in particular in developing 
countries,
<P>
The second session, chaired by Prof. Mohan Munasinghe from Sri Lanka, 
focused on the assessment of health and environmental impacts from 
energy systems.  The presentations pointed out the progress made in 
assessing health and environmental impacts of energy chains for 
electricity generation.  In particular, the increasing awareness of 
potential damages to health and the environment from electricity 
systems has led to extensive in-depth studies aiming towards 
analysing, measuring and valuing these impacts.  Moreover, 
methodologies and computer tools have been implemented to support 
integrated electricity system analysis for decision making.  Progress 
have been made on valuing health and environmental impacts as a means 
for integrating these aspects into economic comparisons of alternative 
electricity strategies.  The examples provided by China and Brazil 
demonstrate that health and environmental concerns are indeed 
addressed in developing countries and that measures are taken to 
assess, alleviate and mitigate the impacts.  However, Prof. Munasinghe 
stressed in his concluding remarks, summarising the presentations and 
discussions, that scientists and analysts have still a long way to go 
for helping decision makers.  More has to be done in: investigating 
comprehensively transboundary and global issues such as greenhouse gas 
emissions and impacts; assessing and valuing very long term effects 
that might arise from chemical and radioactive waste disposal for 
example; and exploring all potential impact pathways.  Uncertainties 
prevailing on data and models make it impossible to give definitive 
answers to all questions and decision makers remain responsible for 
making the final judgements and trade offs.  There is a need for more 
co-operation and exchange between analysts and decision makers aiming 
to transfer adequate information and messages from analytical studies 
to those responsible for policy making.
<P>
The software demonstrations and poster sessions provided the 
participants with concrete illustrations of the capabilities of 
decision aiding computer tools and of their application in decision 
support studies for the power sector.
<P>
The coming technical sessions will shed more light on integrated 
frameworks for comparative assessment and their implementation in the 
decision making process.
<P>
<A NAME="sum2">
<HR>
<P>
<B>Wednesday, 18 October 1995</B> <I>Highlights on the greenhouse gas emission issues</I></A>
<P>
Dr. Yoshji Uchiyama from the Central Research Institute of Electric Power
Industry (Japan) presented figures on greenhouse gas emissions from electricity
generation and supply systems that highlighted the advantages of hydro, nuclear
power and solar photovoltaic as compared to fossil fuel systems. Dr. Uchiyama
showed that, taking into account the entire energy chains and carrying out life cycle
analysis: coal, oil and gas systems emit respectively some 270, 190 and 180 grams of
carbon per kWh generated. On the other side, hydropower, nuclear power and solar
photovoltaic emit respectively some 5, 6 and 35 grams of carbon per kWh.
Dr. Uchiyama pointed out that technological improvements are expected to reduce
significantly the greenhouse gas emissions from electricity systems. LNG combined
cycle will emit 140 grams of carbon per kWh as compared to 180 g/kWh with currently
used gas fired chains. The progress are even more significant for nuclear power and
photovoltaic. Advanced nuclear reactors with closed fuel cycle will emit some 2 to 3
grams of carbon per kWh (versus 6 g/kWh with current nuclear technology) and
photovoltaic systems, using amorphous silicon, will emit 8 grams of carbon per kWh
(versus 35 g/kWh with photovoltaic power plants in operation at present).
<P>
Similar figures and conclusions were presented by Dr. Stefan Hirschberg from
the Paul Scherrer Institute (Switzerland) drawing from a life cycle analysis of
electricity generation chains existing in Switzerland. Dr. Hirschberg showed that
nuclear power emits some one hundred time less greenhouse gases than hard coal
chains and ten time less than presently used solar systems. Dr. Hirschberg pointed
out the importance of life cycle analysis, showing that for fuel cycles other than fossil
the power plant contribution to greenhouse gas emissions is insignificant while the
other steps of the chain are responsible for all or the major share of these emissions
owing to energy and material consumption. In the Swiss context, expected
technological improvements will reduce greenhouse gas emissions by some 30% for
the coal fired and nuclear systems; for solar systems, a reduction by a factor of five of
greenhouse gas emissions is expected with the introduction of amorphous silicon panels.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
</BODY>
</HTML>
 

 




