http://nesihp01.iaea.or.at:80/worldatom/thisweek/preview/desc01.html 193.81.60.210 19970114175859 text/html 6581
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Tue, 14 Jan 1997 17:58:30 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.4
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Symposium on Electricity Health and the Environment
</TITLE>
<META name="author" content="quevenco@adpo1.iaea.or.at">
<META name="expires" content="31 October 1995">
<META name="url" content="http://www.iaea.or.at/worldatom/thisweek/preview/desc01.html">
<META name="type" content="edited">
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<CENTER>
<H2>International Symposium on Electricity, Health and the Environment:
<BR>
Comparative Assessment in Support of Decision-Making
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=-1>Vienna, Austria, 16-19 October 1995</FONT>
</H2>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<B><A HREF="#scope">Objectives & Scope</A>
<P>
<A HREF="#table">Time Table</A>
<P>
<A HREF="summary1.html>Summary of Sessions</B></A>
<P>
<I>Click <A HREF="/worldatom/inforesource/pressrelease/prn17.html">here</A> to see the Press Release, and <A HREF="/worldatom/inforesource/dgspeeches/dgsp1995n10.html">here</A> to read the Director General's opening statement to the Symposium.</I>
</CENTER>
<P>
<A NAME="scope">
<HR>
<P>
<H3>Objectives & Scope</H3></A>
<P>

It is now recognised that market forces alone do not allow to fully reflect economic, social, health and environmental
aspects in technology choices. The need for comparative assessment of different energy chains in the process of decsion making for the power sector has been highlighted by a number of international fora. The implementation of
comparative assessment in support of decision making calls for enhancing co-operation between analysts and policy makers. Recognising the importance of these issues, many international,
regional and national organisations have established programmes of work on data bases, analytical models and improved methodological framework for comparative assessment.
<P>
The inter-agency joint project (DECADES) on data bases and methodologies for comparative assessment of different energy sources for electricity generation was established in this context by nine international
organisations: the European Commission (EC), the Economic and Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific (ESCAP), the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), the International Bank for 
Reconstruction and Development (IBRD), the International Institute for Applied Systems Analysis (IIASA), the Nuclear Energy Agency of the OECD (OECD/NEA), the Organisation of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC),
the United Nations Industrial Development Organization (UNIDO), and the World Meteorological Organization (WMO). The overall objective of the DECADES project is to build capabilities for incorporating economic,
health and environmental aspects in the process of decision making for the power sector.
<P>
This Symposium is convened by the sponsoring organisations, in the framework of the DECADES project, in order to enhance and strengthen information sharing and co-operation between interested and affected parties in the field
of electricity demand analysis and supply planning, aiming at implementing sustainable policies in the power sector, taking into account economic, social, health and environmental aspects.
<P>
The main objective of the Symposium is to bring together senior experts in the field of electricity system analysis and planning, for exchanging information and views on:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>Key issues to be addressed in electricity system analysis for policy making;
<LI>The need for comparative assessment and integrated approaches;
<LI>The feedback from experience in developing comparative assessment methodologies and using them in support of policy making.
</UL>
<P>
The Symposium will offer a forum to present and discuss the findings and conclusions from international, regional and national programmes and projects on comparative assessment of different energy systems. The presentations will
address key issues related to comparative assessment in the power sector, methodologies and data required, and the implementation of sustainable
policies.
<P>
The round table will draw some conclusions and indicate areas in which further work needs to be undertaken, in particular by international organisations, in the field of comparative assessment aiming towards the implementation of enhanced decsision making processes for the power sector.
<P>
Poster sessions will illustrate specific issues and concrete applications of comparative assessment and software demonstrations will provide information on state-of-the-art computer tools, data bases and analytical models, which are available for
assisting planners and decision makers.
<P>
The proceedings, containing keynote addresses, invited papers, poster presentations and a summary of the round table discussions, will be published as soon as possible after the Symposium.
<P>
<A NAME="table">
<HR>
<P>
