<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>IAEA Yearbook 1996 Foreword by Hans Blix</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#ffffff>
<H2>Foreword
<P>
<SMALL>
<I>by the Director General</I>
</SMALL>
</H2>
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<BLOCKQUOTE>	On 26 April 1986, an accident occurred at a nuclear power plant in Ukraine and the
	world became aware of the name 'Chernobyl'. The IAEA has played a major part in
	the subsequent compilation and dissemination of scientifically assessed information
	about the causes and the consequences of this accident. The results of this work, and
that of other national and international organizations, were brought together at an
international conference which was convened by the IAEA together with the World
Health Organization and the European Commission and held in May 1996. The aim
was to summarize the present state of knowledge on the consequences of the
accident. An account of the IAEA's involvement over the past ten years forms the
subject of the lead article in the <I>IAEA Yearbook 1996</I>.
<P>
Part A of the Yearbook describes the role played by the IAEA in helping to advance sustainable development by the transfer of nuclear and radiation technology. The introduction to this section this year discusses the application of quality assurance practices to this important work. The main article describes new planning procedures that are being adopted to ensure that these technical co-operation activities are of significant and practical benefit to the States concerned.
<P>
The work routinely carried out by the IAEA on the development and dissemination of nuclear and radiation techniques covers a wide range of subjects - the practical aspects of physics and chemistry, hydrology, industrial applications, human health, and food and agriculture. Part B of the Yearbook concentrates on food irradiation and the use of nuclear monitoring techniques in programmes for improving human nutrition. Irradiation of foodstuffs is gaining acceptance as a viable alternative to other means of preserving foods and eradicating pest infestation. Nuclear techniques offer new ways of determining the best approaches to food supplements in areas of malnutrition.
<P>
Part C of the Yearbook deals with nuclear power and its fuel cycle and waste management technology. The section on nuclear power describes developments during 1995 in a wide range of countries. It also details the IAEA's work on the comparative health and environmental impacts of different types of energy systems. Of particular interest this year in the fuel cycle area is the report that the downturn in world uranium activities that has lasted for more than 15 years may be coming to an end. In the waste management section, emphasis is given to the technology of
environmental restoration of sites after contamination resulting from past nuclear
	activities.
<P>
A discussion of different aspects of the safety of nuclear power and of the uses of
	radiation is to be found in Part D, <I>The Nuclear Safety Review</I>. This section starts
	with a discussion of the concept of a global safety culture, dealing with international
	conventions and safety standards, and the advisory services offered by the IAEA. It
	also covers a number of topical issues concerning the safety of nuclear power plants,	
	radiation safety and the safety of radioactive waste management practices. Attention
	is devoted here again to the problem of radioactive residues from past nuclear		
	weapons production and testing and from uranium mining and milling.	
<P>
	The prevention of the proliferation of nuclear weapons is a matter of concern to all	
	countries. As in previous years, Part E of the <I>IAEA Yearbook 1996</I> deals with the		
	IAEA's major contribution to the non-proliferation regime - international safe
	guards. In addition to a summary of events in 1995, there are articles on the training	 
	of safeguards inspectors and on the 'Clean Laboratory' which has been built at the	
	IAEA's Safeguards Analytical Laboratory at Seibersdorf to take full advantage of the	
	sensitivity of modern analytical techniques being used to measure very low levels of		
	radionuclides - an important element in the new procedures recently adopted for		
	strengthening safeguards. Part E also contains a description of IAEA activities designed to assist Member States in preventing traffficking in nuclear materials.
	<P>		
	As in previous years, the final part of the Yearbook gives background information on		
	the IAEA - the framework within which it continues to carry out its programme.		
	<P>	
	The last thirty-nine years have seen many developments in the role of the IAEA,	 
	with a range of activities being introduced to meet changes in the outside world. As	 
	it prepares to mark its fortieth anniversary in 1997, the IAEA continues to adapt its	 
	priorities to meet the challenge laid down in its Statute: to "...seek to	
	enlarge the contribution of atomic energy to peace, health and prosperity throughout	 
	the world."	 
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>Hans Blix
</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR NOSHAD SIZE=1>
</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
