<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Sources of Radioactive Waste 
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER>
<H3>
Sources of Radioactive Waste
</H3>
</CENTER>
<HR NOSHADE>
<UL>
<B><I>Low and Intermediate level waste</I></B>
<P>
<LI><B>short lived (half life of less than 30 years)</B>: 
therapy equipment and machines containing radioactive
material; some types of sealed radiation sources; slightly
contaminated rags, discarded protective clothing etc.; nuclear
power plant operation waste, such as filter sludges,
evaporator concentrates, and spent chemical resins.
<P>
<LI><B>long lived (half life of greater than 30 years)</B>: 
waste materials similar to above contaminated with sufficient
amounts of long lived radionuclides with half-lives exceeding
30 years.
<P>
<LI>most LILW from nuclear power plants is categorized as
short lived.  Long lived LILW arises mainly from spent fuel
reprocessing.
<P>
<B><I>High level waste</I></B>
<P>
<LI>most HLW is in the form of spent nuclear fuel from power
plants destined for direct disposal.  Liquid HLW is also
generated during spent fuel reprocessing and is subsequently
solidified.  HLW in practice is considered long lived.
</UL>
<P>
<HR>
</BODY>
<HTML>
</DOC>
