</UL><P><HR width=40% NOSHADE><CENTER><B>DUTIES AND RESPONSIBILITIES</B><HR width=40% NOSHADE><B><I>In general</I></B></center><P>
Under the guidance of the Head of the Nuclear Fuel Cycle and Materials Section, to formulate and implement the economic and environmental aspects of the Agency's nuclear fuel cycle programme, including inventory of plutonium and emerging problems.

<P><CENTER><B><I>In particular</I></B></CENTER><P>- To organize symposia, seminars, technical committees and advisory groups as well as other scientific or technical meetings in the subject area and to prepare documents and technical reports;<BR>
- To keep abreast of the technology and practice to carry out the above responsibilities;<BR>
- To assist in providing advice to Member States, at their request, with respect to the above responsibilities and on technical assistance as required for specific projects and/or training courses;<BR>
- To maintain existing liaison with national and international organizations with regard to the above responsibilities;<BR>
- To provide assistance as required to other activities of the Division within the scope of his/her knowledge and experience.<BR>




<P><HR width=25% NOSHADE><center><B>QUALIFICATIONS</B><HR width=25% NOSHADE></center><P><B>Essential:</B>	Ph.D., or equivalent, in physics, chemistry or metallurgy with orientation towards nuclear engineering.  At least 10 years of experience in the subject area.  Excellent communication skills in English.  Ability to participate effectively in a multi-cultural team.

<BR><B>Desirable:</B>	Ability to formulate efficiently general concepts in the assignment area.  At least two years experience at an international level.  Good report writing skills and ability to handle a personal computer.  Familiarity with the politically sensitive issues associated with the management of plutonium.

<BR><B>Languages:</B>	Fluency in English, French, Spanish or Russian is essential.<P>


