<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Vacancy Notice No.:	96/076	
</TITLE></HEAD><BODY bgcolor=#ffffff><center><font color=#545454><b>
<i>Applications are invited from suitably qualified women as well as men</I></B></font>
</center><HR NOSHADE><center><FONT SIZE=+2>	Waste Regulatory Officer</FONT><BR><FONT SIZE=+2>Vacancy Notice No.: 96/076	
</FONT><BR><strong>Grade:</strong>	P-4
<HR NOSHADE><strong>Organizational Unit</strong><br>	Waste Safety Section
	Division of Radiation and Waste Safety
<BR></CENTER><P><UL><LI><B>Date:</B>10 October 1996<LI><B>Closing Date:</B>	10 February 1997    
<LI><B>Reporting Date:</B>	as soon as possible	
<LI><B>Duty Station:</B>	Vienna
<LI><B>Type of Appointment:</B>	Fixed-term
<LI><B>Duration of Appointment:</B>	Three years
<LI><B>CCOG Code:</B>	1.B.13
</UL><P><HR width=40% NOSHADE><CENTER><B>DUTIES AND RESPONSIBILITIES</B><HR width=40% NOSHADE><B><I>In general</I></B></center><P>
Under the supervision of the Head of the Waste Safety Section, to provide advice and assistance on the regulatory aspects of waste safety.

<P><CENTER><B><I>In particular</I></B></CENTER><P>- To assist in implementation of the Agency's programme on disposable waste safety;<BR>
- To prepare relevant standards and guides as part of the Radioactive Waste Safety Standards (RADWASS) programme;<BR>
- To assist, as appropriate,  in the preparation and implementation of international conventions;<BR>
- To organize symposia, seminars, technical committees, advisory groups and other scientific and technical meetings;<BR>
- To participate in safety and advisory missions to Member States and, in particular, to evaluate and make recommendations on national legislation and regulatory arrangements for radiation and waste safety;<BR>
- To develop and conduct training programmes;<BR>
- To collaborate when needed with other international organisations;<BR>
- To provide advice on and assist in Technical Co-operation projects;<BR>
- To assist in other work of the Division as may be assigned.<BR>

<P><HR width=25% NOSHADE>


<B>NOTE:</B>	The incumbent of the post may be exposed, in the performance of his/her work, to radiation or radioactive substances and will be submitted to an appropriate monitoring programme, according to the Agency's Radiation Protection Rules and Procedures.



<P><HR width=25% NOSHADE><center><B>QUALIFICATIONS</B><HR width=25% NOSHADE></center><P><B>Essential:</B>	University degree in nuclear, chemical or other sciences related to the duties of the post.  At least 10 years experience in radioactive waste safety or radiation protection.  Experience in the preparation of regulatory documents.  Good report writing and editorial capabilities.<BR>

<B>Languages:</B>	Fluency in English is essential.  Knowledge of French, Russian or Spanish is also desirable.<P>
<HR NOSHADE><P>Remuneration is quoted in annual amounts in US dollars 
                          and is deemed to be exempt from National Income Tax.
