<HEAD>
<TITLE>Vacancy Notice No.: 97/001</TITLE>
<META name="docid" content="97/001">
<META name="author" content="adpi">
<META name="expires" content="1997-05-15>
<META name="type" content="edit">
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<CENTER>
<FONT COLOR=#545454>
<B><I>Applications are invited from suitably qualified women as well as men</I></B></FONT>
</CENTER>
<HR NOSHADE>
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+2>Medical Radiation Physicist</FONT>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>Vacancy Notice No.: 97/001</FONT>
<BR>
<STRONG>Grade:</STRONG>	P-3
<HR NOSHADE>
<STRONG>Organizational Unit</STRONG>
<BR>
Dosimetry Section, Division of Human Health
<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
<UL>
<LI><B>Date:</B> 15 January 1997
<LI><B>Closing Date:</B> 15 May 1997
<LI><B>Reporting Date:</B> as soon as possible	
<LI><B>Duty Station:</B> Vienna
<LI><B>Type of Appointment:</B> Fixed-term
<LI><B>Duration of Appointment:</B>	Three years
<LI><B>CCOG Code:</B>	1.J.06.f
</UL>
<P>
<HR width=40% NOSHADE>
<CENTER>
<B>DUTIES AND RESPONSIBILITIES</B>
<HR width=40% NOSHADE>
<B><I>In general</I></B>
</CENTER>
<P>
Under the supervision of the Head of the Dosimetry Section, to assume
the responsibility for the standardization of measurements with
brachytherapy equipment and sources and their dissemination to
members of the IAEA/WHO Network of Secondary Standard Dosimetry
Laboratories (SSDLs) in Member States.  The incumbent should also
provide support for the measurements and
analysis of results within the framework of the IAEA/WHO TLD postal service
for dose quality audits in radiotherapy institutions, and for
Research and Technical Co-operation projects in the field of
dosimetry and medical radiation physics.

<P>
<CENTER>
<B><I>In particular</I></B>
</CENTER>
<P>
- To participate in the development and implementation of laboratory
procedures for measurements with brachytherapy equipment and sources
at the Agency's Dosimetry Laboratory and to carry out calibrations of
brachytherapy equipment upon request by SSDLs in Member States.  This
task assumes active involvement in the Agency's Dosimetry Laboratory
quality assurance programme;
<BR>
- To participate in the Agency's Dose Assurance programme using the
IAEA/WHO TLD postal service, including its extension to quality
audits in the field of brachytherapy and radiation protection.  This
task assumes active involvement in TLD measurements and procedures
and in the training of fellows in the Agency's Dosimetry Laboratory
in TLD techniques;
<BR>
- To help to organize consultant meetings, training courses and seminars, and
to edit publications in the field of brachytherapy and medical
radiation physics;
<BR>
- To act as technical officer for Agency-sponsored research contracts
in the field of dosimetry and medical radiation physics;
To act as technical officer for Technical Co-operation projects in
developing Member States;
<BR>
- To carry out surveys of literature related  to standardization measurements
and quality control programmes in brachytherapy, radiation
protection, x-ray diagnosis and external radiotherapy dosimetry;
<BR>
-To prepare scientific reports, manuals and other documents related to
the fields of brachytherapy dosimetry and medical radiation physics;
To support the training of fellows in calibration techniques other
than brachytherapy and TLD at the Agency's Dosimetry Laboratory.
<P>
<HR width=25% NOSHADE>
<CENTER>
<B>QUALIFICATIONS</B>
<HR width=25% NOSHADE>
</CENTER>
<P>
<B>Essential:</B>	University degree (at the level of M.Sc.) in medical
radiation physics or engineering, at least 6 years of documented
practical experience in hospital radiation physics, including brachytherapy, experience in
ionization chamber and TLD measurements;  experience in the purchase
of radiotherapy and medical radiation physics equipment; experience
in the use of computers (the applicant should state what software and hardware)
for statistical evaluation of data, scientific graphics and
databases, and word processing; experience in research in the fields above, with
peer-reviewed publications in English-language journals; ability in
technical administration and management of paperwork.

<BR>
<B>Desirable:</B>	Ph.D. in medical radiation physics; experience in
diagnostic x-ray dosimetry;  good knowledge of metrology of radiation
dosimetry; experience in teaching and familiarity with problems
specific to developing countries;  experience at international level.

<BR>
<B>Languages:</B>	Fluency in English, French, Russian or Spanish
essential.Excellent command of written and spoken English essential.
<P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P>
Remuneration is quoted in annual amounts in US dollars and is deemed to be exempt
from National Income Tax.
<P>
<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=10 CELLSPACING=10 CELLPADDING=10>
<TR>
