<HEAD>
<TITLE>Vacancy Notice No.1:	96/098</TITLE>
<META name="docid" content="96/098">
<META name="author" content="adpi (public information)">
<META name="expires" content="1997-02-24">
<META name="type" content="edit">
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<CENTER>
<FONT COLOR=#545454><B><I>Applications are invited from suitably qualified women as well as men</I></B></FONT>
</CENTER>
<HR NOSHADE>
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+2>Director</FONT>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>Vacancy Notice No.1:	96/098</FONT>
<BR>
<STRONG>Grade:</STRONG>	D-1
<HR NOSHADE>
<STRONG>Organizational Unit</STRONG>
<BR>
Division of Human Health - Department of Research and Isotopes
<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
<UL>
<LI><B>Date:</B> 10 December 1996
<LI><B>Closing Date:</B>	10 February 1997
<LI><B>Reporting Date:</B>	as soon as possible	
<LI><B>Duty Station:</B>	Vienna
<LI><B>Type of Appointment:</B>	Fixed-term
<LI><B>Duration of Appointment:</B>	Three years
<LI><B>CCOG Code:</B>	1.H.
</UL>
<P>
<HR width=40% NOSHADE>
<CENTER>
<B>DUTIES AND RESPONSIBILITIES</B>
</CENTER>
<HR width=40% NOSHADE>
<P>
Under the general direction and policy of the Director General and the Head of the Department of Research and Isotopes, the incumbment is responsible for directing the activities of the Division of Human Health, which are:
<P>
<CENTER>
<B><I>In general</I></B>
</CENTER>
<P>
To plan, supervise, co-ordinate and direct activities under the
Agency's programme on "Human Health".  These activities include:
<P>
<DL>
<DD>-	Nuclear medicine techniques, both <I>in vivo</I> and <I>in vitro</I>, with
special emphasis on their clinical applications in developing
countries;
<P>
<DD> -	Radiation therapy relevant to the needs of both developing
and developed
countries;
 <P>
<DD>-	Applied radiation biology techniques for raising health
standards in developing countries;
<P>
<DD>-	Radiation dosimetry for radiation therapy and industrial applications;
<P>
<DD>-	Nuclear techniques in nutritional and health-related
environmental studies.
</DL>
<P>
<CENTER>
<B><I>In particular</I></B>
</CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<DL>
<DD>- To direct the personnel of the Division and to monitor the progress
of different scientific programmes;
<P>
<DD>- To provide scientific advice on the research programmes as well as
technical assistance programmes;
<P>
<DD>- To supervise the scientific organization of conferences, symposia,
seminars, training courses and workshops as well as scientific
information exchange;
<P>
<DD>- To prepare with Division staff the programme budget estimates,
financial plans and relevant reports;
<P>
<DD>- To co-ordinate organizational and administrative arrangements with
the sections of the Division;
<P>
<DD>- To be responsible for the efficient management of human and financial
resources;
<P>
<DD>- To co-ordinate the Agency's activities with other UN organizations,
especially WHO, FAO and UNEP, as well as with national, regional and
international medical societies involved in the medical applications
of nuclear techniques;
<P>
<DD>- To provide advisory services to developing Member States.
</DL>
<P>
<HR width=25% NOSHADE>
<CENTER>
<B>QUALIFICATIONS</B>
<HR width=25% NOSHADE>
</CENTER>
<P>
<B>Essential:</B> Advanced university degree in medicine (M.D.) with 15
years experience in nuclear medicine or radiation oncology as well
as in medical research and teaching.  Senior Professor, or
equivalent, with wide experience as a scientific and administrative
manager of a large research institution.  Familiarity with, and
understanding of, the needs of developing countries.
<BR>
<B>Desirable:</B> Working experience at the international level.
<BR>
<B>Languages:</B> Fluency in English, French, Russian or Spanish essential.
<HR NOSHADE>
<P>
Remuneration is quoted in annual amounts in US dollars  and is deemed to be exempt from National Income Tax.<P>
