<html>
<title>IAEA Laboratories</title>
<body>
<center>
<IMG SRC=/worldatom/images/research.gif alt="IAEA Research Laboratories">
</center>
<P>
<hr>
Alone among international organizations within the UN system, the IAEA operates its own nuclear research and
service laboratories to support the safe and effective transfer of technologies to its Member States. Laboratories
at the IAEA's headquarters in Vienna and in Seibersdorf, Austria, provide a diversity of scientific and technical
services related to food and agriculture, physical and chemical sciences,  hydrology and nuclear instrumentation.
Another laboratory in Monaco carries out studies related to the marine environment. A research centre administered by UNESCO in
Trieste, Italy promotes the transfer of advanced scientific knowledge and skills in the sciences.
<hr>
<H2>Contents:</H2>
<DL>
<DT><IMG SRC=/worldatom/images/triblue.gif align=bottom>
<a href=#item1><B> IAEA Laboratories at Seibersdorf and Vienna</B></a>
<P>
<DL>
<DD><IMG SRC=/worldatom/images/trired.gif align=bottom> Agriculture Laboratory
<DD><IMG SRC=/worldatom/images/trired.gif align=bottom> Physics Chemistry Instrumentation Laboratory
<DD><IMG SRC=/worldatom/images/trired.gif align=bottom> Safeguards Analytical Laboratory
<DD><IMG SRC=/worldatom/images/trired.gif align=bottom> Clean Laboratory
<DD><IMG SRC=/worldatom/images/trired.gif align=bottom> Isotope Hydrology Laboratory
<DD><IMG SRC=/worldatom/images/trired.gif align=bottom> Training Programmes at the IAEA Laboratories
</DL>
<P>
<DT><IMG SRC=/worldatom/images/triblue.gif align=bottom>
<a href=#item2><B> IAEA Marine Environment Laboratory</B></a>
<P>
<DL>
<DD><IMG SRC=/worldatom/images/trired.gif align=bottom> Technical Co-operation
<DD><IMG SRC=/worldatom/images/trired.gif align=bottom> Analytical Quality Assurance Service
<DD><IMG SRC=/worldatom/images/trired.gif align=bottom> Method Development
<DD><IMG SRC=/worldatom/images/trired.gif align=bottom> Marine Processes
<DD><IMG SRC=/worldatom/images/trired.gif align=bottom> Nuclear Techniques in the Study of Non-Nuclear Contaminants
</DL>
<P>
<DT><IMG SRC=/worldatom/images/triblue.gif align=bottom>
<a href=#item3><b> International Centre for Theoretical Physics</b></a>
</DL>
<P>
<a name=item1>
<hr>
<H2>IAEA Laboratories at Seibersdorf</H2>
<hr>  
<P>
Established in 1962, the Agency's Seibersdorf Laboratories help implement the IAEA 's programmes in food and agriculture,
human health, environmental and earth sciences, radiation protection, and safeguards. They provide scientific services
including quality control and chemical and radiochemical analyses and conduct research and development related to
the IAEA's coordinated research programmes and technical cooperation activities. The Laboratories also train scientists
from developing countries with emphasis on transferring nuclear and related techniques necessary to carry out Agency projects
<P>
Activities at the Laboratories emphasize quality assurance procedures meant to instill confidence in the use of transferred technologies as well as 
to provide reliance on data generated by national and regional laboratories. Efforts are made to focus on techniques which contribute to environmental
monitoring and protection and lead to sustainable development practices. The Agency's laboratories cooperate and collaborate with
laboratories in developing countries which have been identified as focal points for the creation or strengthening
of national or regional infrastructures in nuclear energy fields. At its headquarters in Vienna, the IAEA also operates
an Isotope Hydrology Laboratory in support of its programs in areas of water resource management and development.
<br>
The IAEA Laboratories in Seibersdorf include the:
<P>
<H3>Agriculture Laboratory</H3>
<P>
The Agriculture Laboratory, operated jointly with the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) of the United Nations,
 provides technical and scientific support to joint programmes of the IAEA and FAO in soil fertility, 
irrigation and crop production, plant mutation breeding, animal production and disease diagnosis, insect and pest control and 
agrochemicals and residues. It places particular emphasis on developing appropriate nuclear and related
techniques that could be trasnferred to developing countries. The laboratory includes five branches:
<DL>
<DD><IMG SRC=/worldatom/images/triblue.gif align=bottom> Soil Science Unit
<DD><IMG SRC=/worldatom/images/triblue.gif align=bottom> Plant Breeding Unit
<DD><IMG SRC=/worldatom/images/triblue.gif align=bottom> Entomology Unit
<DD><IMG SRC=/worldatom/images/triblue.gif align=bottom> Agrochemicals Unit
<DD><IMG SRC=/worldatom/images/triblue.gif align=bottom> Animal Production Unit
</DL>
<H3>Physics, Chemistry, Instrumentation Laboratory</H3>
The Physics, Chemistry, Instrumentation (PCI) Laboratory provides technical and experimental support to IAEA 
programmes in physical and chemical sciences, industry and earth sciences and human helath. It also performs specialized tasks for the 
Departmnet of Nuclear Energy in the field of radiation safety and protection, for example, measuring radionuclides in food
and the environment. The PCI Laboratory also helps the Department of Safeguards in special analyses and mechanical and equipment construction.
The PCI laboratory has four branches:
<DL>
<DD><IMG SRC=/worldatom/images/triblue.gif align=bottom> Chemistry Unit
<DD><IMG SRC=/worldatom/images/triblue.gif align=bottom> Instrumentation Unit
<DD><IMG SRC=/worldatom/images/triblue.gif align=bottom> Dosimetry Unit
<DD><IMG SRC=/worldatom/images/triblue.gif align=bottom> Isotope Hydrology Unit
</DL>
<H3>Safeguards Analytical Laboratory</H3>
The Safeguards Analytical Laboratory (SAL) analyzes samples taken from key measurement points of the fuel cycle
to meet the requirements of safeguards accounting verification. To accommodate the large number of samples to 
be analyzed, SAL works with a network of analytical laboratories that comply with IAEA quality assurance and are nominated
by Member States. In cooperation with the training section of the Department of Safeguards, SAL also conducts a
training programme for safeguards inspectors to demonstrate the requirements for acquiring and handling samples and for making on-site destructive analyses.
SAL is comprised of the:
<DL>
<DD><IMG SRC=/worldatom/images/triblue.gif align=bottom> Chemical Analysis Unit
<DD><IMG SRC=/worldatom/images/triblue.gif align=bottom> Isotopic Analysis Unit
</DL>
<H3>Clean Laboratory</H3>
Construction has started on a Clean Laboratory in Seibersdorf which will serve as the focal point for environmental
monitoring for safeguards purposes. It will receive, analyze  and distribute to the network of analytical laboratories 
special samples taken during ad hoc safeguards inspections to confirm the absence of undeclared nuclear 
activities. 
<P>
<h3> Training Programmes at the IAEA Laboratories</h3>
<dl>
<dt><IMG SRC=/worldatom/images/triblue.gif align=bottom> <B>In-Service Training of Fellows</B>
<dd>In this type of training, fellows work alongside staff scientists for 1-12 months in the application of specific
nuclear techniques to the solution of practical problems.
<P>
<dt><IMG SRC=/worldatom/images/triblue.gif align=bottom> <B>Inter-regional Training Courses</B>
<dd>On the average, some 20-30 participants, each from a different country, attend lectures and practical exercises
covering selected topics over a 5-8 week period.
<P>
<dt><IMG SRC=/worldatom/images/triblue.gif align=bottom> <B>Group Training</B>
<dd>Groups of 6-8 fellows are trained on practical topics for 2-6 months. The fellows receive technical tutoring, attend 
technical lectures and gain extensive hands-on experience under the close supervision of the laboratory's 
technical staff.
</dl>
<P>
<i>More information about the IAEA's Laboratories and training programs are available from Seibersdorf Laboratory, 
A-2444 Seibersdorf, Telephones: (+43) 2254-2251-2, (+43) 2254-3361-4, (+43) 2254-3951-6; Fax: (+43) 1-234564.</i>
<p>
<a name=item2>
<hr>
<H2>IAEA Marine Environment Laboratory</H2></a>
<hr>
<P>
The IAEA Marine Environment Laboratory (IAEA-MEL) in Monaco is the only marine laboratory within the United Nations
system. Besides carrying out IAEA core programmes, IAEA-MEL also responds to requests for technical and experimental assistance from
other UN agencies. The application of nuclear and isotopic techniques and the improved understanding of marine radioactivity continue to be central to the Laboratory's
work. The Laboratory has been engaged in studies assessing the impact of radioactive waste dumping in the 
Arctic Seas, marine effects from the Gulf war, the carbon cycle and greenhouse effect, Chernobyl radioactivity in the oceans, and pesticide run-off and toxicity to
coastal fisheries.<P>
<H3>Technical Co-operation</H3>
In co-operation with the IAEA Department of Research and Isotopes, IAEA-MEL organizes training courses on 
topics such as marine radioecology, marine pollutant monitoring.
The general aim is to increase the capacity of the international community to monitor and control pollution of the 
marine environment via a mixed programme of in-house and field training, equipment installation, and maintenance 
and laboratory visits.
<h3>Analytical Quality Assurance Service</h3>
The IAEA-MEL is a worldwide centre for data quality assurance for all kinds of chemical contaminants, both nuclear
and non-nuclear. It carries our regional exercises in the Mediterranean, the Gulf area, the western Pacific, west
and central Africa, and the Black Sea.
<h3>Method Development</h3>
IAEA-MEL continues to work on developing new, more efficient and more cost-effective laboratory methods for monitoring, studying
and controlling marine pollutants, both nuclear and non-nuclear. Inductively coupled plasma mass spectrometry is at the forefront of this
activity. It is also developing rapid mapping techniques for use in emergency response, as well as routine surveillance and mineralogical 
prospection.
<h3>Marine Processes</h3>
In order to obtain information on the behaviour and fate of radionuclides and other potential pollutants in the 
marine environment, scientists at IAEA-MEL participate in numerous scientific cruises in the Mediterranean, North Atlantic,
and the Black Sea region, sometimes under the aegis of IAEA co-ordinated research programmes. The Laboratory also participates in 
the "International Mussel Watch" experiment, which studies the global pattern of pesticide residue contamination by 
measuring concentrations of these substances in samples of the common mussels from countries throughout the world.
<h3> Nuclear Techniques in Studies of Non-Nuclear Contaminants</h3>
There is an increasing need in developing countries to gain knowledge in nuclear techniques for studying non-nuclear contaminants.
Among areas in which the Laboratory helps in this transition are in tracer studies using radiolabelled compounds, immunological
analyses and stable isotope techniques and multi-element analyses using mass spectrometry.
<P>
<i>More information about IAEA-MEL can be obtained by contacting: IAEA Marine Environment Laboratory, 
19, Avenue des Castellans, MC 98000 Monaco, Telephone: (+33) 92 05 2222; Fax: (+33) 92 05 7744; E-mail: mel@unice.fr.</i>
<p> 
<a name=item3>
<hr>
<H2>International Centre for Theoretical Physics (ICTP)</H2></a>
<hr>
<p>
Located in Trieste, Italy, ICTP is an important insitution for the exchange of and transfer of advanced scientific knowledge and
skills. It is active in many scientific fields, including  fundamental physics, condensed matter physics, mathematics,
physics and energy, physics and the environment, physics and the living state, and applied physics and technology.
Over 3,600 scientists participated in research and training activities carried out at the Centre in 1994, of which 55%
came from developing countries. In 1994, it also distributed 45,000 items of scientific literature to 500 institutions in
93 developing countries. The Centre operates with funding from the Italian government, UNESCO and the IAEA. Administrative
function was transferred from the IAEA to UNESCO in January 1996.
<P>
<i>More information about ICTP is available on the
<a href=http://www.ictp.trieste.it>ICTP World Wide Web Server.</a></i>
<P>
<CENTER>
<HR SIZE=1 NOSHADE>
