<head>
<title>PR/6 - 17 April 1995 - IAEA Director General Calls on States Belonging to the
Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT) to Provide Firm, Uninterrupted Basis for the Agency's NPT-Related Services at the Treaty's Review and Extension Conference</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<hr size=1 noshade>
17 April 1995 (PR 95/6) 
<h3>IAEA Director General Calls on States Belonging to the
Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT) to Provide Firm,
Uninterrupted Basis for the Agency's NPT-Related Services
at the Treaty's Review and Extension Conference</h3>
<hr noshade size=1>
<P>
The Director General of the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), Dr. Hans Blix, today
(17 April) called upon States attending the NPT Review and Extension Conference in New York
(17 April-12 May) to ensure that the various key services of the Agency provided under the NPT
can continue without interruption.
<p>         
Speaking at the opening session of the Conference at the United Nations in New York,
Dr. Blix said the IAEA has a central, statutory role both in promoting the peaceful applications
of nuclear energy and in helping to prevent its military use, thus serving as a vital instrument
for the implementation of the NPT.
<p>         
Dr. Blix said "the Agency must be enabled, through adequate resources, and
strengthened and streamlined safeguards, effectively to verify that non-proliferation pledges are
respected, and, thereby, to create confidence among the parties." He noted in this context that
the IAEA's Board of Governors had at its meeting last month endorsed the general direction of
recent proposals for a major safeguards development programme. These proposals, he said,
would -- if accepted -- significantly increase the level of assurance about the absence of undeclared
facilities although they would be less intrusive than the inspections mandated by the Security
Council in Iraq.
<p>         
The Director General suggested that the Agency's verification capacity could
also be employed in implementing such nuclear disarmament agreements as might be reached in
pursuance of Article VI of the NPT.
<p>         
The Agency would of course continue in parallel, he added, to serve as a principal
intergovernmental channel for the transfer of peaceful nuclear technology among NPT parties
and of assistance to developing nations.
<p>         
In the course of his speech, the Director General reviewed in particular the lessons learnt
in Iraq, the Democratic People's Republic of Korea and South Africa for the evolution of the
safeguards system and its future strengthening, both in terms of methodology and technology:
access to information and access to sites remained, however, the crucial factors for the
effectiveness of the system.
<p>         
<i>Note: The full text of the Director General's speech is available from the Agency's New York
liaison office or from the Division of Public Information in Vienna or on the <a href=/worldatom/inforesource/dgspeeches/>Internet</a></i>.
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE="1">
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG BORDER="0" SRC="/worldatom/images/backtomain.jpg" ALT="Back to listing of Press Releases"></A>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE="1">
