<P>
<HR>
<A NAME=summary>
<CENTER>
<H3>SUMMARY OF MEETINGS<BR>
<FONT SIZE=-1>THURSDAY, 21 SEPTEMBER</FONT></H3>
</CENTER>
<P>
<B>PLENARY: 7th meeting</B>
<P>
The Conference resumed its discussion of item 7 of the agenda, "General debate and annual report for 
1994".  Statements were made by the delegates of the Libyan Arab Jamahiriya, the Czech Republic, 
Algeria, Indonesia, Myanmar, Slovakia, Ecuador, Norway, Nigeria, Bangladesh, Uruguay, Mongolia, 
Kenya, Colombia, the United Republic of Tanzania and Namibia.   
<P>  
<B>COMMITTEE OF THE WHOLE: 5th meeting</B>
<P>
Under agenda item 14, "Scale of assessment of Members' contributions towards the Regular Budget", 
the Committee agreed to recommend the draft resolution contained in document GC(39)/24/Rev.1, thus 
superseding its earlier decision on this item.
<P>
The Committee concluded its consideration of item 21 (b), "Personnel questions: women in the 
Secretariat" and agreed to recommend the draft resolution contained in document GC(39)/42.
<P>
The Committee resumed its consideration of item 22, "Amendment of Article VI of the Statute".
<P>
<B>PLENARY: 8th meeting</B>
<P>
The Conference continued with item 7 of the agenda, "General debate and annual report for 1994".  
Statements were made by the delegates of Kuwait, Slovenia, Peru, Jordan, Paraguay, Guatemala, 
Nicaragua and Iraq.  A statement was also made by the representative of the Agency for the Prohibition 
of Nuclear Weapons in Latin America.  The Conference decided to keep open this item to enable the 
Plenary to consider the draft resolution on nuclear testing introduced by the delegate of the Philippines 
in document GC(39)/26/Rev.1.  
<P>  
<B>COMMITTEE OF THE WHOLE: 6th meeting</B>
<P>
The Committee continued its consideration of item 22, "Amendment of Article VI of the Statute", and 
agreed to recommend the draft resolution contained in document GC(39)/44.
<P>
The Committee continued its consideration of agenda item 19, "Strengthening the effectiveness and 
improving the efficiency of the safeguards system".
<P>
<HR>
<CENTER>
<A NAME=announce>
<H3>ANNOUNCEMENTS</H3></A>
</CENTER>
<P>
<B>INFORMAL MEETINGS</B>
<P>
The following informal meetings have been scheduled for today (Friday):
<P>
<TABLE BORDER=1 CELLPADDING=3 WIDTH=100%>
<TR align=left><TH>
Group<TH>Time<TH>Location</TR>
<TR><TD>WEOG<TD>9.00 a.m.<TD>Conference Room 0</TR>
<TR><TD>EU<TD>2.15 p.m.<TD>Conference Room N</TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<STRONG>GENERAL ARRANGEMENTS</STRONG>
<p>
General information about the Conference, such as the location of meeting rooms and offices, telephone 
extensions and the various services, may be obtained at the Information Desk (second floor, No. 11, 
extension 2141).
<P>
Delegates may wish to note that information about the Agency's General Conference, including major 
reports and documentation, is globally available on-line through the Agency's Internet-based Web services. 
These services are being demonstrated near the Foyer Cafe A on the second floor of the ACV.
<P>
<B>IDENTIFICATION BADGES</B>
<P>
In the interest of security, conference participants are requested to wear their badges when entering the 
ACV and for as long as they are in the building.  Members of delegations and other participants who are in 
possession of a valid VIC ground pass will not need additional identification.  All other participants are 
requested to obtain their identification badges from the Registration Desk on the ground floor, No. 1, at the 
ACV.  Badges will be issued from 8.30 a.m. onward.
<P>
<STRONG>SPEAKERS' LIST FOR PLENARY MEETINGS</STRONG>
<P>
At plenary meetings the President calls upon speakers to each item in the order in which they have entered 
their names on a written list.  Delegates wishing to speak to an item are requested to inform Mr. A. Don, 
on the second floor, No. 7, extension 2133, who will also have a table in the Plenary Hall near the podium.  
Delegates of ministerial rank will be given preference.
<P>
Microphones have been placed on all tables.  Delegates are requested to use them for voting by roll call, for 
explanation of vote, for interventions in the exercise of the right of reply and for procedural motions.
<P>
At other times, and especially during the general debate, delegates are requested to deliver their statements 
from the rostrum.  Delegates about to make their statement are asked to come forward to the front when the 
preceding speaker is making his concluding remarks and wait at the table marked "next speaker".
<P>
<STRONG>USE OF RADIO RECEIVERS IN MEETING ROOMS</STRONG>
<P>
In meeting rooms A, B, C, M, N and O of the ACV, portable radio receivers will be available, enabling 
participants to follow the proceedings in the original language and in the working languages of the 
Conference.  As these receivers must be serviced between meetings, participants are requested not to 
remove them from the meeting rooms.
<P>
<STRONG>SMOKING</STRONG>
<P>
Participants are requested not to smoke in the meeting rooms.
<P>
<B>VOLUNTARY CONTRIBUTIONS TO THE TECHNICAL CO-OPERATION FUND FOR 1996</B>
<P>
To enable up-to-date information to be provided to the General Conference regarding voluntary 
contributions to the Technical  Co-operation Fund for 1996, the Contributions Officer, Ms. C. Langer, will 
be available to receive pledges in her office (second floor, No. 13, extension 2112) or, immediately before 
and during plenary meetings, at a desk in the Plenary Hall near the podium.
<P>
<B>INFORMATION EXHIBITS AND DEMONSTRATIONS </B>
<P>
Information exhibits will be organized by the Agency during the General Conference.  These exhibits 
comprise information and demonstrations on the following subjects:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>IAEA and the Internet;
<LI>25 Years of the IAEA Nuclear Information System (INIS);
<LI>The IAEA Illicit Trafficking Information System;
<LI>Power Reactor Information System (PRIS);
<LI>Databases on Safety Issues for WWER and RBMK reactors; and
<LI>Personnel Information.
</UL>
<P>
The exhibits are located near the Foyer Cafe A on the second floor of the ACV and will be open daily from 
9.00 a.m.  to 5 p.m.
<P>
<B>GENERAL FACILITIES AND SERVICES AT THE ACV</B>
<P>
Incoming telephone calls for participants will be taken by the Information Desk.  The number is 212 44 00 
extension 2141 (through dialling).  Incoming telegrams will be delivered to the Information Desk and the 
addressee will be paged.
<P>
A Post Office is located on the ground floor, No. 3, for the dispatching of outgoing telegrams and 
facsimiles.  For outgoing long-distance telephone calls, participants are asked to contact the Post Office.
<P>
Restaurant facilities are available at the ACV for the duration of the session.  Lunch will be served in the 
restaurant on the first floor, No. 1, from 11.30 a.m. to 2.30 p.m. at the same price as at the VIC.  Snacks and 
beverages are available all day at the ACV Snack Bar, which is located on the second floor, No. 10.
<P>
The Bank Austria provides banking services on the ground floor, No. 4, extension 3310 from 8.30 a.m. to 
11.30 a.m. and from 12.30 p.m. until 5.00 p.m. Monday to Friday.  Banking services will also be available 
on Saturday if there is a meeting.
<P>
Emergency medical attention is obtainable in the Medical Service at the VIC from 8.30 a.m. until the close 
of the last meeting of the day (VIC building F, seventh floor, telephone number 71, extension 22222).  For 
emergency assistance at other times, delegates may apply to the security guard at the VIC (telephone 
number 71, extension 99).
<P>
<B>ISSUE OF VIC COMMISSARY CARDS TO HEADS OF DELEGATIONS</B>
<P>
Heads of delegations are advised that cards entitling them to make purchases at the VIC Commissary will 
be issued by the United Nations Security Pass Office, which is situated in Room G0E10 of the VIC, from 
10 a.m. to 4 p.m. for the duration of the session.  After receipt of the card, the bearer is requested to validate 
it at the Commissary Service Counter (VIC, Room F-151) from 12 noon to 6 p.m.
<P>
<B>SECURITY</B>
<P>
Security equipment has been installed at the ACV.  All personnel attending the Conference are requested to 
co-operate with the security personnel.
<P>
<B>ACCESS TO THE ACV FROM THE VIC</B>
<P>
Participants can enter the ACV via the VIC through connecting doors located in Building G of the VIC.
<P>
<B>PARKING AT THE ACV</B>
<P>
Parking space is reserved on parking decks 1 and 2 of the ACV.  For official cars with chauffeurs, red 
stickers entitling the cars to be driven to the main entrance of the ACV will be issued.  For other cars, 
drivers should obtain an entry parking ticket on arrival at the parking decks.  Upon presentation of a 
General Conference or VIC ground pass, this ticket can be exchanged for a weekly parking ticket, free of 
charge, at the IAEA Registration Desk on the ground floor of the ACV. 
<P>
<B>PUBLIC TRANSPORT</B>
<P>
It is possible to travel between the VIC and Vienna's city centre by underground train (U-Bahn).  Tickets 
may be purchased at U-Bahn stations or in advance, in quantities of five or ten, at most Austrian tobacco 
shops (identified by the round AUSTRIA TABAK sign).  Weekly tickets are also available.
<P>
<B>EMERGENCY STAIRCASES IN THE ACV</B>
<P>
Participants are advised that the emergency staircases in the ACV cannot be used for going from one floor 
to another.  Although they can be entered on any floor, the only exits are at the -3 (i.e. lowest) level.  They 
should therefore be used only in a real emergency.
<P>
<B>END OF EUROPEAN SUMMERTIME</B>
<P>
Delegates are advised that, in Austria, the clocks will be set back one hour in the night from Saturday, 
23 September to Sunday, 24 September.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
