<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN">

<html>

<head>
<title>NF - Subscriptions</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h2><img src="/worldatom/images/fusion.gif" align=middle> <font size=7>n u c l e a r&#160;</font><font size=4>&#160;&#160;</font><font size=7> f u s i o n&#160;</font></h2>
<p><font size=4><strong>MANUSCRIPT SUBMISSION</strong></font><font size=2> </font></p>
<hr>

<p><strong>Manuscript Preparation: </strong>Standard <em>NF </em>practice requires SI units, or common derived units such as the centimetre and the megampere. Incidental use of 
non-standard units plus a conversion factor is acceptable.</p>
<p>The names of authors should follow, if necessary, the standard IAEA transliteration guides, available on request. The full names of Chinese authors should be 
provided.</p>
<p>Abstracts should summarize the contents of the article in 300 words or less, and should contain the principal objectives, the methodology employed, 
the results, the new findings and the main conclusions. General, well known information, should be accommodated in the introduction.</p>
<p>If a reference has five authors or less, all the authors may be listed. If there are more than five, the first author followed by et al. should be given. (<em>NF</em> practice 
regarding the number of authors has varied over the years; the guidance given above reflects the IAEA standard.) Authors' names are printed in all capital letters, 
surname first. Journal references should use customary abbreviations, such as <em>Nucl. Fusion</em>, <em>Phys. Rev. Lett.</em>, plus volume number, year in parentheses and page 
number. Unpublished material -- laboratory reports, theses, papers not yet published -- should be cited with full titles, place and year. Citations of reports should 
also contain laboratory prefix and number, date of issue, etc. </p>
<p>References to books should contain authors' or editors' names, the full title, the name and location of the publisher, the year of publication and the page number (if 
appropriate). References to personal communications should be avoided.<br>
<br>
Terms and acronyms found in widely available text-books need not be explained.Less widely known terms should be explained.<br>
<br>
All figures should be camera-ready, labelled so as to be fully legible after reduction for the journal (usually to one column width (8 cm)), on separate sheets and 
numbered consecutively with arabic numerals in the order in which they are mentioned in the text. Tables must have a heading and be numbered consecutively with 
roman numerals.<br>
<br>
Footnotes to tables should be indicated by raised letters (not numbers or asterisks) and set immediately below the table itself. Footnotes to the text should be 
numbered consecutively with raised arabic numerals. </p>
<p><a href="math.htm"><strong>Guidelines for Mathematics</strong></a> </p>
<p><br>
<strong>Machine Readable Submission:</strong> <em>NF</em> encourages the submission of machine readable text, figures and tables after acceptance of a manuscript for publication. 
Our internal text processing uses LaTeX plus encapsulated PostScript or bitmap graphics for graphic material. We can handle other formats from the more common 
PC and MacIntosh programs, but at reduced efficiency. Submission on floppy disks, especially MS-DOS disks, or through ftp (file transfer protocol) is preferable 
to electronic mail, unless the files are smaller than approximately 100 kilobytes. <br>
<br>
Our LaTeX style files are available at our ftp site, or by e-mail, for authors interested in submitting preliminary or final manuscripts that are as close as possible to 
the published result. Please contact the <em>NF</em> office if you have questions about using our style files.
<p>
<strong>Proofs:</strong> The submitting author will receive proof of the typeset manuscript, including figures and tables. The proofs will have corrections marked, and often queries. Please respond to any queries, and add additional corrections if necessary, using a pen of distinguishing colour, usually red. Return the marked proofs by mail or 
express service. The use of colour precludes sending or receiving proofs by fax. Return with the proofs the billing information for page charges and the order for any extra reprints. <br>
Contacting the Editorial Office: The postal address, effective also for courier services, is </p>
<p><em>Nuclear Fusion</em><br>
International Atomic Energy Agency,<br>
Wagramerstrasse 5, P.O. Box 100,<br>
A-1400 Vienna, Austria. </p>
<p><br>
Our e-mail address is <a href="mailto:nf@adpo1.iaea.or.at">nf@adpo1.iaea.or.at</a>.<br>
The telefax number is +43 1 2060 2 9655;<br>
the telephone number of the office is +43 1 2060 2 6195 and that of the editor is +43 1 2060 2 6198.<br>
Some information of interest to <em>NF</em> readers and authors will be found at our ftp site, <a href="ftp://ftp2.iaea.or.at/pub/nf">ftp2.iaea.or.at/pub/nf </a><br>
and on our worldwide web site: <a href="http://www.iaea.or.at/worldatom/inforesource/fusion">www.iaea.or.at/worldatom/inforesource/fusion</a>.<br>
<br>
October 1996</p>
<hr>
